            <h1>Cybersecurity Programs</h1>
        </header>
        <main>
            <h2>Introduction</h2>
            <p>Cybersecurity involves protecting systems, networks, and data from digital attacks and unauthorized access. As technology advances, the need for cybersecurity professionals has become critical, leading to its development as a significant academic discipline and career path.</p>
            <h2>Academic Emergence</h2>
            <p>Cybersecurity began gaining recognition as an academic major in the late 1990s and early 2000s with the rise of the internet and digital threats. By the 2010s, many universities offered dedicated cybersecurity programs, focusing on areas like network security, ethical hacking, and digital forensics.</p>
            <h3>Colleges in Ohio Offering Cybersecurity Programs.</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Ohio State University</li>
                <li>University of Cincinnati</li>
                <li>Case Western Reserve University</li>
                <li>University of Dayton</li>
                <li>Wright State University</li>
                <li>Kent State University</li>
                <li>Cleveland State University</li>
                <li>Columbus State Community College</li>
                <li>Sinclair College</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Salary Expectations for New Graduates</h3>
            <p>The demand for cybersecurity professionals is high, making it a lucrative field for new graduates. Entry-level cybersecurity analysts in the United States typically earn between $60,000 and $80,000 annually, with some specialized roles offering starting salaries up to 
            $100,000. This reflects the growing need for skilled professionals to combat evolving cyber threats.</p>
